## 🆕 Changes Made in This Implementation

### Problem Before the Changes

The command actor **had no HTTP endpoint** to trigger operations. It only had:
```
GET /healthz  → Kubernetes liveness probe
GET /readyz   → Kubernetes readiness probe
```
The only way to trigger a command was to publish a message directly onto the NATS bus — not practical for testing or direct integration.

---

### Change 1: New file `pkg/resources/commands.go`

Created a new REST resource file (mirroring `diagnoses.go`) with:

| Function | What it does |
|---|---|
| `BindCommandHandler()` | Creates a Gorilla mux router with the `POST /commands` route registered |
| `runCommand()` | HTTP handler — deserializes request, sets up callbacks, publishes to NATS, waits for response |
| `newCommandEmit()` | Publishes a `CommandRequest` to NATS and wires up request/response correlation |
| `mergeWithDefaults()` | Merges user params with zero-value defaults so missing enum fields don't fail (see bug below) |
| `createCommandResponse()` | Formats the response JSON sent back to the HTTP client |

---

### Change 2: Updated `cmd/actors/command/main.go`

**Before:**
```go
func startService(logger loggingAPI.Logger) {
    mux := http.NewServeMux()
    mux.HandleFunc("/healthz", ...)
    mux.HandleFunc("/readyz", ...)
    // No business endpoints
}
```

**After:**
```go
func startService(logger loggingAPI.Logger, commandCommands *commands.Commands) {
    commandRouter := resources.BindCommandHandler(commandCommands)  // ← new

    mux := http.NewServeMux()
    mux.HandleFunc("/healthz", ...)
    mux.HandleFunc("/readyz", ...)
    mux.Handle("/", commandRouter)  // ← mounts /commands route
}
```

Also added initialization of shared services and `commands.Commands` in `main()`.

