## 💡 Summary in Plain English

> **Diagnosis actor** handles both read-only checks (ping, BGP state, interface counters) and some device operations like reboot. But it works in a **fire-and-return** style — it triggers the operation, gets an immediate success/failure answer, and returns. It does not monitor what happens after.

> **Command actor** is for operations where you need to **track the outcome**. For a reboot, it triggers the reboot, then actively pings the device to confirm it shut down and came back online — this can take up to 30 minutes. During that time, it sends progress updates to Kafka so other systems know what's happening.

Both work the same way at the HTTP layer — you POST a JSON request, and you get a JSON response. The complexity is all hidden inside the actor pipeline.

