### How the `commandType` String Maps to the Handler Function

This is the "magic" that confuses newcomers. **No code in `commands.go` references `NeReboot()` directly.** The routing is entirely string-based:

```
You send:       "commandType": "io.leitstand.actor.events.commands.NeRebootCommandRequest"
                                          │
                                          │ same string
                                          ▼
Pipeline has:   .On(schemas.NeRebootCommandRequest_1.GetName(), commands.NeReboot)
                         │                                            │
                         │ evaluates to the same string               │ the function
                         ▼                                            ▼
                "io.leitstand.actor.events.commands.NeRebootCommandRequest"  →  commands.NeReboot()
```

The `schemas.NeRebootCommandRequest_1` is a constant in the pod-events library that evaluates to `"io.leitstand.actor.events.commands.NeRebootCommandRequest"`. The router simply does a map lookup: `handlers["io.leitstand.actor.events.commands.NeRebootCommandRequest"]` → `commands.NeReboot`.

If you send a `commandType` that no `.On()` registered, the router has no match and the message is silently dropped (or sent to a dead-letter queue).

